result.execSummary:
The defendant Julie A Shackelford was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manuf/Deliver Schedule I, II Narcotics [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

The defendant is to have NO CONTACT with Neely Stroede and/or Christian Walker.   The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician.

Defendant to undergo an alcohol and other drug assessment and comply with any further counseling and/or treatment as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.

records.addlTxt: 12:10 pm case called. Defendant Julie A Shackelford in court with attorney David C. Rashid.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Agreement reached and stated on the record. Defendant wishes to waive the preliminary hearing. Court questions the defendant and accepts waiver of right to preliminary hearing. Court has read the complaint, finds probable cause, and enters an order binding the defendant over for trial. Information filed, Attorney Rashid confirms receipt, waives formal reading.   Defendant advised of permissible punishment.  Plea QN reviewed w/Defendant.  Plea colloquy entertained.  Collateral consequences explained. Chapter 950 compliance addressed.  Plea: No Contest to Count 1.  Court accepts plea and enters JOC. Court dismisses and reads-in Count 2. Sentencing argument by DA Blader. Sentencing argument by Attorney Rashid. Statement by defendant's daughter. Statement by defendant. Court makes statement and sentences the defendant to: SWD and places the defendant on probation for a period of 3 years. CONDITIONS: 70 days WCJ, with Huber as authorized by the jail where the sentence is served, No Good Time Credit. To begin no later than October 14, 2016 at 8:00 pm. Court does not object to jail transfer. Court will not authorize EMD.  No contact with Neely Stroede and/or Christian Walker. AODA and follow through, The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician. Terms of Agent. Costs plus $300.00 Drug Buy Money to be paid within 60 days or payment plan. Drug Buy Money joint and several with Neely Stroede. DNA Sample and Surcharge ordered by the Court.  Defendant advised of right to expunge DNA record through the Department of Justice. Appeal Rights Given.

Evidentiary hearing on September 14, 2016 at 12:00 pm.

Case Called @ 2:18 PM: Defendant Julie A Shackelford in court with attorney David C. Rashid.  Steven Paul Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court has reviewed the PT filings submitted and notes the State's 2nd MIL (904.04(2)) filed with Response filed by Atty Rashid.  Court believes further evidentiary hearing may be required.   Further statement by Atty Rashid.  Court finds offered evidence satisifies first level of Sullivan analysis; evidence is relevant satisfying 904.01 and be relevant for establishing Def's alleged knowledge and role and dispelling Def's contention for exoneration; 904.02 evidence is relevant for dispelling that anticipated defense.  Finally, Court finds what has been offered would be far more probative than prejudicial.  Court will issue cautionary instruction to the jury.  Evidence introduction and testimony discussed. Court will treat evidentiary hearing as Miranda/Goodchild.  Court to review video CD interview in advance of hearing - counsel to file for Court's review.  Counsel prepared to Stipulate to admission of evidence that identifies controlled substances.  Def agrees to not object to introduction of hygiene lab reports.  Def confirms Stipulation and waives right to challenge the analyst findings - right of confrontation waived.  ADA states there may not be specific lab reports.  Def clarifies and agrees to State's claim of what the controlled substances are.  State is relieved from the burden of proving up the specific substances.  Def willing agrees and stipulates to those facts being proven.  Voluntary stipulation.  Court accepts agreement and stipulation reached as to the identity of the substances.  No objection voiced to the admission of the video of the purported transaction.  Brady vs. Maryland discussed as to offers extended.  Atty Rashid admits receipt and intends to use if needed.  908.01(3) statements discussed and must be previously disclosed - if not - will not be admissible.  Any 906.09 issues will be taken up at the next evidentiary hearing.  Motion must be filed for the Court to address at next hearing.  Evidentiary hearing scheduled for September 14, 2016 at 12:00 pm.
